<a href="javascript:card_browser(68)">Goblin Backstabber</a> x2  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> BIDDING:  Bid 4 or 5 (almost always wins) and pull Sam out with Green Dragon Inn. . . try not to let him die because you will need him to remove burdens.  I use Aragorn, KIE because he heals Sam every turn, that way Sam can remove more burdens and I can play more Power According to His Stature.  It is important to go first to force your opponent to play catchup and play into the hands of the moria beatdown.<br>
<br>
SITE CHOICES: <br>
<br>
Green Dragon Inn:  There to pull Sam.<br>
Breeland Forest :  No stealth events (I usually dont get this site though because I usually go first).<br>
Rivendell Waterfall:  Tempt your opponents to move three sites at a time . . . believe me its dangerous.  Also none of the other options helped me.<br>
Moria Lake:  Just because its annoying and it has a good number.<br>
Bridge: so I can check for the balrog and look at my deck . . . hehehe<br>
Dimrill Dale: Free first orc!<br>
Anduin Wilderland:  No archery, archery bad.<br>
Shores of Nen Hithoel:  Almost always stops opponent in their tracks because five orcs are easy to get down.<br>
Slopes of Amon Hen: Well the moria orcs are already cheap, so I might as well make the uruk-hai cheap since none of the other sites really help moria.  Noone really gets to this site anyway :)<br>
<br>
FELLOWSHIP:<br>
<br>
Both of these decks are made to play through cards quickly in order to set up a beatdown faster.  The fellowship is all about the card PATHS.  Elrond helps you draw up to get them, and Bilbo shuffles them back into your deck.  Both Frodo AND Elrond heal Bilbo, and the extra copies heal Elrond and Bilbo, so they can both be used multiple times per turn.  It is easy to keep two or more copies of PATHS in your hand at a time, which ends up being really nasty for your opponents minions.  Aragorn and Gandalf will win skirmishes with their swords, also Glamdring and Sting can keep the twilight pool low while Sam removes burdens added by opponent or by PATHS.  There is a high number of weapons and such because they go down easily so I can cycle faster.  Servant of the Secret Fire wins skirmishes for you too.  Pretty easy deck to play.  However there is one thing that is the natural enemy of PATHS, Saruman&#39;s Snows.  That&#39;s why I have Albert Dreary x2, because nothing else will cancel it except Boromir&#39;s Cloak and I&#39;m not playing Boromir.  Trust me on this one, ALBERT DREARY IS ABSOLUTELY VITAL TO THE DECK BECAUSE OTHERWISE I WILL LOSE TO SARUMAN&#39;S SNOWS.  Got it?  Alright, now don&#39;t tell me to drop albert dreary for an extra sleep caradhras.  After Elrond and Bilbo are down, this deck should be able to move two sites a turn since it adds very little pool once it is set up.  I sometimes let my opponent get a site ahead of me in the early game so that I can play on my sites, but that&#39;s really not a big deal because both decks are designed to run smoothly on any adventure path.  Oh yeah if Aragorn gets his bow PATHS is soooooo much better . . . you can shoot someone twice and then play PATHS to kill them (or just shoot them completely dead) although you can usually get multiple PATHS in hand.<br>
<br>
SHADOW:  <br>
<br>
Bit more to explain here.  Now I&#39;m not a big fan of Moria, but I was looking at swarm decks, and I was looking at their weaknesses.  There are really only two big weaknesses to swarm decks.  The first is archery.  The second is any skirmish action that can kill an orc.  Strength doesn&#39;t matter, the objective is to outnumber the opponent.  I found what I think to be the best way around this are Saruman&#39;s Snows and Spies of Saruman, even if it forces me to include a small number of uruk-hai in the deck.  I chose Uruk-Hai that were relatively cheap with good vitality (first of all to be able to exert to put down the conditions, second of all in order to survive past the skrimish phase). If the opponent is playing PATHS or Blade of Gondor or whatnot, Saruman&#39;s Snows will shut them down (especially a deck that uses stealth cards :) and if they are playing archery (very popular) then spies is a fantastic beatdown.  Underdeeps of Moria is used with the Goblin Sneaks to setup a cycle to put orcs back in your deck and then pull them off the bottom.  It works fantastically well and it&#39;s extremely hard to beat.  Goblin Runners add pool, Moria Scouts are free when elves are out and the Backstabbers are huge in dogpiles if you can&#39;t overwhelm.  It&#39;s nasty, and it&#39;s fast.  I play 2x Albert Dreary because of decks like this (and funny, I have never seen anyone else in my area play Albert Dreary *evil laugh*).  Hopefully this deck will make him more popular, but it&#39;s not exactly shut down by him either.  Oh yes, the uruk-hai are also very good for the nifty little damage +1 thing when they gang up with the moria orcs.  Lots of times the fighters are fierce too.  That&#39;s about all.  I appreciate constructive reviews that would tell me how I could make this deck better.  Oh by the way, I do know that when Bilbo shuffles back the PATHS, he messes up the goblin sneak thing, but the minions are still back in my deck and I can use them again later and usually I pull an orc off the bottom with underdeeps as soon as I put it there, so I dont need to worry about Bilbo.  Here&#39;s a slight example of how the underdeeps thing works . . . .<br>
<br>
Play a Goblin Sneak, take another Sneak from discard Pile, put it on bottom of deck<br>
Use Underdeeps to get sneak from bottom of deck, play second sneak, . . . wash, rinse, repeat. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=20410"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=20410" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
